You can use [`static_cast`](https://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/language/static_cast#Notes) to specify which one should be used.

&gt; `static_cast` may also be used to disambiguate function overloads by
&gt; performing a function-to-pointer conversion to specific type, as in
&gt; 
&gt;     std::for_each(files.begin(), files.end(),
&gt;                   static_cast&lt;std::ostream&amp;(*)(std::ostream&amp;)&gt;(std::flush));

e.g.

    doWork(static_cast&lt;void (A::*)(void) const&gt;(&amp;A::foo));
    doWork(static_cast&lt;void (A::*)(void) const&gt;(&amp;A::bar));

Or specify the template argument explicitly.

    doWork&lt;void (A::*)(void) const&gt;(&amp;A::foo);
    doWork&lt;void (A::*)(void) const&gt;(&amp;A::bar);

You may use:

    template &lt;typename T&gt;
    void doWork(void (T::*fun)() const){
        const A a;
        (a.*fun)();
    }

A more generic function template would use `const T a`.

    template &lt;typename T&gt;
    void doWork(void (T::*fun)() const){
        const T a;
        (a.*fun)();
    }

Note that the second version does not assume `A` anywhere.

